  "Idea": "We propose the construction of FinStance-M&A, a large-scale, domain-specific dataset for stance detection in financial M&A events, designed to achieve high inter-annotator reliability and balanced class distribution through a novel integration of active learning, multi-layered annotation protocols, and ontology-guided synthetic augmentation. Unlike general sentiment analysis, stance detection requires identifying whether a text segment expresses support, opposition, or neutrality toward a specific event—here, an M&A announcement. In financial texts, such stances are often implied through hedging language, speculative framing, or indirect endorsements (e.g., 'This acquisition aligns with long-term strategic goals'), making annotation inherently ambiguous. To mitigate this, we introduce a three-tier annotation schema: (1) Stance label (Support/Oppose/Neutral), (2) Speculation level (Factual, Predictive, Hypothetical), and (3) Sentiment polarity (Positive/Negative/Neutral), enabling fine-grained disambiguation and improving consistency. High IAR is achieved via iterative annotation rounds with trained financial domain experts, supported by real-time disagreement dashboards and consensus workshops. Active learning is employed during data curation: an initial model identifies high-uncertainty samples for prioritized labeling, maximizing information gain per annotation. To address class imbalance—especially the scarcity of 'Oppose' instances—we generate synthetic examples using templates grounded in a financial M&A ontology (e.g., derived from SEC filings, analyst reports), ensuring syntactic variation while preserving domain semantics. These synthetic samples are validated by human experts before inclusion. The final dataset will contain at least 50,000 sentence-level instances drawn from diverse sources: earnings call transcripts, regulatory filings (8-K, 10-K), financial news (Reuters, Bloomberg), and analyst commentaries. We will benchmark transformer-based